snippet.textDisplay:
That looks delicious. But all these years of making omnivore meatloaves, I've never sauteed my vegetables before putting them in.
I've made tasty healthy meatloaf recipes by adding diced onion, grated carrot, grated zucchini to lean beef mince. Flavoured with herbs, garlic, stock powder, even oyster sauce (the "Symply Too Good To Be True" recipe books either have a meatloaf recipe with that, or I just make a loaf sized "Rippa Rissole" I guess). Sometimes bread crumbs, evaporated milk and/or eggs to bind it.


The fun part is when you can put boiled eggs or cheese (or vegan substitutes I guess) in the middle of the loaf. And then when you have plenty of flavour going on in the loaf, a simple can of condensed tomato soup can be used as the "glaze". Bonus points if the "glaze" also reaches the potatoes you've placed around your meatloaf to roast.


I think all that would work with either beyond meat, lentils, beans or a combination of all of the above. Heck, you could probably make it with potato and then you wouldn't even need to make mashed potatoes to go with it.

snippet.textDisplay: I was literally eating my leftover lentil loaf and mashed potatoes when I started watching this, I don't use the beyond beef in it, I think its delicious enough without it, mine also has ground up walnuts in it, probably in place of the oat flour, I also take bits and pieces from a few different recipes n make it to my liking. The flax really should be mixed in water though before adding it to the mixture because it's supposed to be an egg replacement so it should be egg like before adding it to bind everything. As far as spices I put a little bit of italian seasoning, but mostly just some oregano, sage, and rosemary, but I taste as I'm mixing it as to not over season like I did the first time making it because I followed the recipe. I also just use canned lentils now cuz I dont want over cooked lentils that are mush and it also saves time.
